content.text: You can access the items of a dictionary by referring to its key name, inside square brackets:
content.html: You can access the items of a dictionary by referring to its key name, inside square brackets:

content.code_html:
thisdict = {
  "brand": "Ford",
  "model": "Mustang",
  "year": 1964
}
x = thisdict["model"]

content.text: There is also a method called get() that will give you the same result:
content.html: There is also a method called get() that will give you the same result:

content.code_html: x = thisdict.get("model")

content.text: The keys() method will return a list of all the keys in the dictionary.
content.html: The keys() method will return a list of all the keys in the dictionary.

content.code_html: x = thisdict.keys()

content.text: The list of the keys is a view of the dictionary, meaning that any changes done to the dictionary will be reflected in the keys list.
content.html: The list of the keys is a view of the dictionary, meaning that any changes done to the dictionary will be reflected in the keys list.

content.code_html:
car = {
"brand": "Ford",
"model": "Mustang",
"year": 1964
}

x = car.keys()

print(x) #before the change

car["color"] = "white"

print(x) #after the change

content.text: The values() method will return a list of all the values in the dictionary.
content.html: The values() method will return a list of all the values in the dictionary.

content.code_html: x = thisdict.values()

content.text: The list of the values is a view of the dictionary, meaning that any changes done to the dictionary will be reflected in the values list.
content.html: The list of the values is a view of the dictionary, meaning that any changes done to the dictionary will be reflected in the values list.

content.code_html:
car = {
"brand": "Ford",
"model": "Mustang",
"year": 1964
}

x = car.values()

print(x) #before the change

car["year"] = 2020

print(x) #after the change

car = {
"brand": "Ford",
"model": "Mustang",
"year": 1964
}

x = car.values()

print(x) #before the change

car["color"] = "red"

print(x) #after the change

content.text: The items() method will return each item in a dictionary, as tuples in a list.
content.html: The items() method will return each item in a dictionary, as tuples in a list.

content.code_html: x = thisdict.items()

content.text: The returned list is a view of the items of the dictionary, meaning that any changes done to the dictionary will be reflected in the items list.
content.html: The returned list is a view of the items of the dictionary, meaning that any changes done to the dictionary will be reflected in the items list.

content.code_html:
car = {
"brand": "Ford",
"model": "Mustang",
"year": 1964
}

x = car.items()

print(x) #before the change

car["year"] = 2020

print(x) #after the change

"brand": "Ford",

print(x) #after the change

content.text: To determine if a specified key is present in a dictionary use the in keyword:
content.html: To determine if a specified key is present in a dictionary use the in keyword:

syntaxHighlighting.text:
thisdict =	{
  "brand": "Ford",
  "model": "Mustang",
  "year": 1964
}
  if "model" in thisdict:  print("Yes, 'model' is 
  one of the keys in the thisdict dictionary")
